<https://data.archives.gov.on.test.gbad.caBorn%20in%20Coniston%2C%20Solski%20was%20educated%20in%20Sudbury.%20Between%201935%20and%201978%2C%20he%20was%20employed%20by%20INCO%20as%20a%20labourer%2C%20tradesman%2C%20foreman%2C%20co-ordinator%2C%20and%20Supervisor%20of%20Central%20Assets%20and%20Surplus.%20Solski%20was%20also%20active%20in%20Local%20598%20of%20the%20International%20Union%20of%20Mine%20Mill%20and%20Smelter%20Workers%2C%20serving%20as%20local%20union%20shop%20steward%2C%20organiser%2C%20vice-president%20treasurer%20and%20eventually%20president.%20He%20was%20also%20Secretary%20of%20the%20Canadian%20Mine%20Mill%20Union%20Council%20as%20well%20as%20Eastern%20Canadian%20Director%20of%20the%20International%20Mine%2C%20Mill%20and%20Smelter%20Workers.%20In%20addition%20to%20labour%20activism%2C%20Solksi%20was%20involved%20in%20local%20politics.%20In%201954%2C%20he%20became%20Councillor%20for%20Coniston%20and%2C%20in%201963%2C%20Mayor%2C%20a%20position%20he%20held%20for%20ten%20years.%20Solski%20also%20served%20as%20Mayor%20of%20Nickel%20Centre%20for%20six%20years.%20Further%2C%20he%20was%20a%20Regional%20Councillor%20and%20President%20of%20the%20Sudbury%20District%20Municipal%20Association.%20He%20also%20acted%20as%20Vice-Chairman%20of%20the%20Regional%20Municipality%20of%20Sudbury%20for%203%20years.%20Solski%20served%20on%20various%20boards%2C%20committees%20and%20commissions%20including%20the%20Hydro%20Commission%2C%20Sudbury%20Regional%20Police%20Commission%2C%20the%20Police%20Governing%20Authority%20of%20Ontario%2C%20the%20Sudbury%20General%20Hospital%20Board%20and%20the%20Canada%20Employment%20and%20Immigration%20Advisory%20Council.%20Solski%20also%20authored%20and%20co-authored%20numerous%20books%20and%20booklets%20such%20as%3A%20The%20Coniston%20Story%3B%20Mine%20Mill%20-%20The%20History%20of%20the%20International%20Union%20of%20Mine%20Mill%20and%20Smelter%20Workers%20in%20Canada%20since%201895%3B%20and%20the%20Industrial%20Communities%20of%20the%20Sudbury%20Basin%3A%20Copper%2C%20Cliff%2C%20Victoria%20Mines%2C%20Mond%20and%20Coniston.%20Solksi%20was%20married%20to%20Irene%20Horrick%20with%20whom%20he%20has%20one%20daughter%2C%20Sandra%20Spratt.%20He%20died%20in%20November%2C%201999.>
  a owl:NamedIndividual .

<https://data.archives.gov.on.test.gbad.caBorn%20in%20Montreal%2C%20Quebec%20Montaigne%20graduated%20in%201936%20from%20St.%20James%20College%20in%20Minneapolis%2C%20Minnesota%20with%20a%20B.A.%20in%20journalism.%20After%20graduation%20he%20worked%20as%20a%20freelance%20journalist%20for%20a%20number%20of%20major%20American%20newspapers%20and%20magazines%2C%20and%20also%20wrote%20radio%20scripts.%20Montaigne%20served%20in%20World%20War%20Two%20as%20a%20member%20of%20a%20Canadian%20artillery%20unit%2C%20and%20while%20in%20Scotland%2C%20married%20Barbara%20Malcolm%20Hope%2C%20a%20native%20of%20Pembroke%2C%20Ontario.%20After%20the%20war%20ended%2C%20they%20settled%20in%20Pembroke%2C%20and%20Montaigne%20began%20work%20with%20radio%20station%20CHOV%20as%20a%20commercial%20representative%2C%20involved%20in%20advertising%2C%20news%20gathering%2C%20writing%20and%20producing.%20In%201948%20Bill%20and%20Barbara%20Montaigne%20opened%20Montaigne%27s%20Flowers%2C%20Gifts%20and%20Photography%20Shop%2C%20where%20he%20focussed%20primarily%20on%20photographing%20local%20events.%20In%20the%201950s%20the%20photography%20part%20of%20the%20business%20expanded%20to%20include%20film%20productions%2C%20sound%20recordings%2C%20and%20television%20journalism%2C%20with%20Montaigne%20freelancing%20for%20CBC%20television.%20He%20also%20became%20more%20active%20in%20photojournalism%2C%20contributing%20work%20for%20magazines%2C%20journals%2C%20and%20local%20newspapers.%20In%20the%201970s%20Montaigne%20involved%20himself%20more%20in%20commercial%20photography%2C%20focussing%20upon%20weddings%2C%20portraits%20and%20graduations.%20In%201979%20he%20published%20a%20book%20entitled%20%22How%20to%20Begin%20and%20Operate%20a%20Successful%20Commercial%20Photography%20Business.%22%20Montaigne%20operated%20his%20photography%20business%20until%20his%20death%20in%201988.>
  a owl:NamedIndividual .

